      <div id="mainContent" class="main column clearfix"> 
       <div class="content1">
        <p>The Call for Presentations for the 2016 VMI STEM education Conference opens May 4, 2016 and closes July 15, 2016. The accepted workshops will be posted on this page after August 1, 2016.<br>&nbsp;<br>In the meantime, to get a sense of the types of workshops that will be available, please review the 2015 conference workshops below.</p>
        <p id="radETempNode">&nbsp;<strong><a href="/uploadedFiles/Conferences/STEM/VMI CLE STEM Program-web.pdf" title="2015 STEM Education Conference Program">2015 VMI STEM EDUCATION CONFERENCE PROGRAM - DOWNLOAD</a></strong></p>
        <p>2015 STEM Resources are in the process of getting uploaded within each of the workshop descriptions below (expand the workshop name to reveal its description, info about presenters and links to their respective resources).</p>
        <p>Few of the resources were in PDF format, so as those are converted, they will get uploaded ;).&nbsp; Please check this site often for the updates.</p>
        <p><em>*A big thank-you to everyone who provided us with a submission - their contributions are a big part of what makes this conference so successful and highly rated!*</em>&nbsp;<br><br>RESOURCES:&nbsp; Due to many files which had formats incompatible to our server for storage, we have provided a dropbox location from where workshop resources may be downloaded.&nbsp; You will need a dropbox account/profile to use this cloud storage site.&nbsp; Please email:&nbsp; roycm@vmi.edu if you have problems.&nbsp; </p>
        <p><a href="https://www.dropbox.com/sh/3k83pw7dt71vkiw/AAAe_BilAA_df7Rc90BHBzHQa?dl=0" title="https://www.dropbox.com/sh/3k83pw7dt71vkiw/AAAe_BilAA_df7Rc90BHBzHQa?dl=0" target="_blank">2015 STEM Education Conference Dropbox - Workshop Resources</a></p>
        <p>&nbsp;</p>
       </div>
       <div class="accordion">
        <div>
         <h2>2015 STEM Workshops</h2>
         <a href="#" class="readMore">3D Printing in a Middle School Makerspace - Grades 5-8, Administrators</a>
         <div class="more">
          <p>3D printing: Moving students from Replicator to Creator/ lecture presentation 3D printers are absolutely mesmerizing. They light up and make wonderful sounds. Students of all ages are drawn to the idea of a 3D printers. They want to try it out but they have no idea how to do it. During this session we will walk you through the hurdles we encountered once we added a 3D printer into our Makerspace. We will share with you how we are slowly moving our students from just printing what someone else made to creating their own original creations to print. We will even show you how to digitize yourself to 3D print.<br><br>This workshop covers technology for teachers and administrators with students in grades 5-8. <br><br>Instructors: <br><br><img align="right" src="/uploadedImages/Conferences/STEM/Susan Jinks_web.jpg?n=8118" alt="2015 Susan Jinks, Ph.D." title="2015 Susan Jinks, Ph.D.">-Susan Jinks, Ph. D., Instructional Technology Specialist, Falls Church City Public School&nbsp;</p>
          <blockquote>
           <div>
            Dr. Susan Jinks is an instructional technology specialist at Mary Ellen Henderson Middle School (MEH) in Falls Church City, VA. Jinks helped her school deploy a 1:1 laptop program during the 2014 school year. In addition, she successfully co-wrote a grant to establish a Makerspace in the school library. She recently became a Google Educator and Google for Education Certified Trainer. Her doctoral work focused on the factors that lead to the perception of learning within a graduate online course.
           </div>
          </blockquote>
          <p>-Lori Fogle, Librarian/Media Specialist, Falls Church City Public School</p>
         </div>
        </div>
        <div>
         <a href="#" class="readMore">Add a New Dimension to Your Students' Learning: 3D Printing in the Elementary Classroom - Grades 3-5</a>
         <div class="more">
          <p><img align="right" src="/uploadedImages/Conferences/STEM/Karen Heathcock web.jpg?n=5141" alt="Karen Heathcock 2015 STEM" title="Karen Heathcock 2015 STEM">Attendees will experience a variety of web-based software applications that students can use to integrate 3D printing into their learning. Come see how 3D printing can augment instruction and bring learning to life no matter what grade level or content area you teach. We will discuss how to incorporate 3D printing across subjects, troubleshoot common 3D printing issues, and provide practical advice on how to get students independent and productive with 3D printing. Creative ways to fund 3D printers and filament will also be explored.</p>
          <div>
           <br>This workshop covers Technology for teachers with students in grades 3-5.
          </div>
          <p>Instructor: &nbsp;Karen Heathcock, Gifted Resource Teacher, Albemarle County Public Schools</p>
          <blockquote>
           <p>Karen is a Canadian who pursued teaching as a second career. She graduated from the Teacher's College at York University in Toronto, Ontario before moving to the United States in 2001. In addition to being endorsed in elementary education, she is also endorsed in economics, gifted education, and reading. Karen enjoys collaborating with classroom teachers to foster each student's ability to think critically, to problem solve (independently and collaboratively), to question at increasingly higher levels, and to create/make with confidence and flexibility. These are the skills that make kids deeper thinkers, lifelong learners, and more productive, engaged citizens.&nbsp;</p>
          </blockquote>
         </div>
        </div>
        <div>
         <a href="#" class="readMore">Angling Your Neighborhood - Grades 6-8</a>
         <div class="more">
          <p>For middle school mathematics teachers, finding a STEM application for angle relationships can be a struggle. During this workshop, attendees with participate in a lesson called “Angling Your Neighborhood”. This lesson uses inquiry to discover different angle relationships. As attendees discover these relationships, they are challenged to use them to develop a neighborhood roadway system. By mixing inquiry with an engineering task, attendees are able to help their students develop the appropriate mathematics knowledge while applying that knowledge in a creative design and build activity. By participating in this hands-on lesson, attendees will be prepared to take this ready-made activity back to their middle school math classrooms. The activity is designed for the Virginia Math 8 Standards of Learning but can be adapted to the needs of sixth and seventh grade math by changing the criteria of the engineering task. </p>
          <p>Workshops covers integrated STEM for teachers with students in grades 6-8.</p>
          <p><img align="right" src="/uploadedImages/Conferences/STEM/Kristine_Vester.jpg?n=3915" alt="Kristine Vester" title="Kristine Vester">Instructor: &nbsp;Kristine Vester, Educator, MathScience Innovation Center</p>
          <blockquote>
           <p>Kristine Vester<strong></strong>is a Mathematics Educator with the MathScience Innovation Center (MSiC) in Richmond, VA. In 2006, Kristine earned her M.Ed. in Curriculum and Instruction, with a focus on mathematics, from VCU. Over a period of 11 years, Kristine has worked in several middle schools, focusing on mathematics and science education. In the Fall of 2008, Kristine joined the MSiC staff. Since then, she has been involved in creating innovative STEM lessons incorporating nanotechnology, engineering and fractals, for the virtual platform and the classroom. She has been a leader in different engineering programs for teachers, such as the VA STEM CoNNECT, as well as developing STEM Career programs for school counselors. Throughout her professional career, Kristine has been involved in developing and presenting professional developments on a local to national level. Her last two presentations were featured at the Regional NCTM Conference and the NSTA STEM Forum.</p>
          </blockquote>
         </div>
        </div>
        <div>
         <a href="#" class="readMore">Astronomical Tools &amp; How to Use Them - Grades 3-8</a>
         <div class="more">
          <p>Today there are a number of astronomical tools (telescopes, cameras, software, websites...) available that an educator can use to enhance their student’s learning experience. It can be a daunting task wading through all the options, and choosing the right one is not always easy. Once you have made your choice learning to use the tool can also be a time consuming task; where do you turn to for help? In this workshop we will give you an introduction to what’s available in the way of tools and resources that are suitable for various education levels. From free to pricey we give you a rundown on what’s out there, the “good, the bad, and the ugly”, and where to get help. We will present the basics of how to choose and use binoculars, telescopes, cameras, and software as well as what to look for, and look out for, when it’s time for you to make your choice. Weather permitting there will be an optional observing session in the evening. (See the schedule for details.)&nbsp;</p>
          <p>This workshop covers technology for educators and administrators with students in grades 3-8.<br><br>Instructors: &nbsp;<br><br><img align="right" title="2015 STEM Gregory Topasna, Ph.D., VMI" alt="2015 STEM Gregory Topasna, Ph.D., VMI" src="/uploadedImages/Conferences/STEM/topasnaga.jpg?n=8743" style="height: 200px;">-Lt. Col. Gregory Topasna, Ph. D., Department of Physics &amp; Astronomy, Virginia Military Institute</p>
          <blockquote>
           <p>Dr. Topasna is a Professor of Physics at Virginia Military Institute in Lexington, VA. He is a graduate from VA Tech with a Ph.D. in Physics and a concentration in astronomy. He has been teaching physics and astronomy since joining the VMI faculty in 2000 and conducts astronomical research on the polarization of starlight and the interstellar medium. Additionally, Dr. Topasna works with Dr. Daniela Topasna in the thin films laboratory at VMI where they fabricate and characterize thin film devices as well as Janus particles.&nbsp;</p>
          </blockquote>
          <blockquote></blockquote>
          <p><img align="right" src="/uploadedImages/Conferences/STEM/Daniela Topasna_web.jpg?n=7775" alt="2015 STEM Daniela Topasna" title="2015 STEM Daniela Topasna">- Lt. Col. Daniela Topasna, Ph. D., Department of Physics &amp; Astronomy, Virginia Military Institute</p>
          <blockquote>
           Dr. Topasna is an associate professor in the department of physics and astronomy at Virginia Military Institute. Her research interests include fabrication and characterization of self assembled thin films. She has presented and authored several outreach activities in physics and nanotechnology. &nbsp;
          </blockquote>
         </div>
