        <div>
         <a href="#" class="readMore">Blending Art, Language Arts and Linear Equations - Grades 5-8</a>
         <div class="more">
          <p><img align="right" title="2015 STEM Tabetha Myers" alt="2015 STEM Tabetha Myers" src="/uploadedImages/Conferences/STEM/Tabetha Myers_web.jpg?n=934">Participants will all be given the same equations and blank paper to graph with NO guidance regarding scale factor. After equations are graphed, instructions will be to create a piece of art that uses color and texture to relate to some aspect of their life. As art is completed, comparisons of the “chevron” that emerges will be relevant to relating the art to the project-based experience. A presentation will follow using students’ work of the “Stained Glass” project. Sixth grade students began with a mini-lesson in art appreciation, followed by graphing the same equations (VDOE) on larger paper. Periodic check-ins using todaysmeet.com were relevant to discuss various problems that students were having while navigating equations. Students gave feedback on each other's art, learning, through the project, slope and y-intercept form and key elements to linear functions from a very elementary understanding (6th – 8th grade curriculum). Students wrote a synopsis of what the artistic elements meant to them and how they chose to use materials and various elements to set the tone of the work of art. Students wrote a paper using google docs relating the art to the mathematics in a formal five-paragraph format. Attendees will take away all handouts/rubrics, etc. Numerous examples of student work will be used to explain the project and extend attendees view of what students can do when given the freedom to think critically and creatively! The session will culminate brainstorming ways that this project can be enhanced or ways students’ work can be published.&nbsp;</p>
          <p>This workshop covers mathematics for teachers with students in grades 5-8.</p>
          <p>Instructor: &nbsp;Tabatha Myers, Teacher, Albemarle County Public Schools</p>
          <blockquote>
           <p>Tabatha has been teaching mathematics and science for ACPS for 12 years and has an B.S. in Liberal Science, Elementary Ed. from Longwood University. In 2007, she received her Master of Education and Math Specialist Endorsement from the University of Virginia. She has taught sixth grade math her entire career, primarily located at the AVID demo school Jack Jouett Middle. She teaches a wide array of both math and science curriculum including all of middle school mathematics.</p>
          </blockquote>
