        <div>
         <a href="#" class="readMore">CAREERS Project-based Learning Program</a>
         <div class="more">
          <p>The Creative and Real-World Engaging Experiences Realized this Summer (CAREERS) program was created for at-risk and low performing 7th and 8th grade students as an alternative to a traditional summer school. Furthermore, research has shown that college and career readiness should be started in the middle school to help assess personal interest and future goals through career exploration. The program hired teachers to create project-based learning units that were created around the 16 career clusters. Each project focused on competencies of problem solving, flexibility, collaboration and time management. It also embedded reading and math skills. The culminating project was for students to select one project and create a visual representation of the process of how they worked to create a project to answer a driving question or solve a challenge. In addition, students researched a potential career cluster of interest and presented it to community members. The hands-on presentation will showcase the many projects that included some STEM PBL (MakerSpace, water rocket science, textile engineering), technologically related projects (t-shirt shop) and the culminating project. Participants will examine the projects at different stations and fill out a handout that will prompt them to ask questions, write observations and how it could be used in other schools. After the activity, the presenters will answer questions, discuss the benefits and lessons learned from the program. The attendees will receive ideas and ways to incorporate project-based learning units that include STEM and technology into their curriculum. The SOLSs covered will be non-fiction reading skills, physical science SOLs and various math standards.</p>
          <p>This workshop covers project based learning for teachers and administrators with students in grades 7-8.</p>
          <p>Instructors: &nbsp;</p>
          <p>- Rory Dippold, Ph. D.,&nbsp;CAREERS Coordinator / Civics &amp; Economics Teacher, Falls Church City Schools</p>
          <blockquote>
           <p>Dr. Dippold is a Nationally Board Certified Teacher who has taught for twelve years in Falls Church City Schools. He is a Civics &amp; Economics teacher who incorporates project-based learning into his curriculum to create authentic learning experiences. In addition, his dissertation was titled, 'Infusing Self-regulation Learning into Project-based Learning' and he currently serves as an adjunct professor at George Mason University. He was recently honored as a Virginia Lottery “Super Teacher” award winner.</p>
          </blockquote>
          <p><img align="right" title="2015 Susan Jinks, Ph.D." alt="2015 Susan Jinks, Ph.D." src="/uploadedImages/Conferences/STEM/Susan Jinks_web.jpg?n=4008">-Susan Jinks, Ph. D.,&nbsp;Technology Instructional Coach, Falls Church City Schools</p>
