         <a href="#" class="readMore">The Chesapeake Challenge - Grades 5-8</a>
         <div class="more">
          Imagine being stranded in the woods with a nearby stream as your only source of water. Would you drink the water? There are many hidden pollutants in our natural water sources that can have a negative impact on your health. Luckily with the advancement in filtration methods, those pollutants can be removed to create safe drinking water. In this STEM challenge, participants will build their own filter and then test its efficiency at removing pollutants from the water. Based upon their results, participants will redesign to improve their filters. Connections will be made to the importance of the Chesapeake Bay ecosystem and the human impacts within its watershed. SOLs: 6.5, 6.7
          <div>
           &nbsp;
          </div>
          <div>
           This workshop covers integrated STEM for teachers with students in grades 5-8.
          </div>
          <p>Instructor: &nbsp;Rachel Martin, Educator and Science Department Head,&nbsp;MathScience Innovation Center</p>
          <blockquote>
           <p>Rachel Martin is an educator and department chair at the MathScience Innovation Center in Richmond Virginia. Her experiential educational philosophy was created after spending a semester in college studying environmental science in Australia where she swam with sharks on the Great Barrier Reef, ate breakfast with a platypus, and became a host to countless leeches while exploring the rainforests of Australia. Thanks in part to the myriad of phenomenal educators in her life, she pursued her Master of Arts in Education degree from the College of William and Mary to pass on the love of learning. Following her teaching experiences in middle school science, she became a biology, earth science and environmental science educator for the MathScience Innovation Center in 2005. Over the past 10 years, Rachel has been involved with numerous keystone projects including fractal geometry, virtual lessons, nanoscience, environmental sustainability and engineering.</p>
          </blockquote>
         </div>
        </div>
