        <div>
         <a href="#" class="readMore">Developing STEM Initiatives in the Rural School District - Grades 3-8, Administrators</a>
         <div class="more">
          <p>In order to implement an effective STEM program in a rural school district, one must understand the nature and needs of such unique communities. This session will discuss the five components of developing a high school STEM program. The first component will focus on the use of incorporating data so that the division recognizes the need for STEM initiatives. This may even include assisting in dissolving traditional district boundaries. Component two will focus on identifying stakeholders who would develop a steering committee, community partnerships (community, local industry and post-secondary education) and an advocate for the process. This component will show that a rural community needs to come together with resources to create a lasting and effective STEM education infrastructure. This leads into the third component, Professional development and fourth component, Technology. It is extremely important that educators within the division adopt and are trained in the effective use of technology and distance learning. The final component is the capstone of the program which includes internships and the inclusion of CTE programs.<br><br>This workshop covers integrated STEM for teachers and administrators with students in grades 3-8.</p>
          <p>Instructors: &nbsp;</p>
          <p>-Thomas Johnson III,&nbsp;High School Assistant Principal/STEM Program Chair,&nbsp;Accomack County Public Schools</p>
          <blockquote>
           <p>Mr. Thomas Johnson III is currently serving as the Assistant Principal for Nandua Middle School in Accomack County. He is the leading advocate and chairperson of the Accomack County Public Schools STEM Academy which is starting the third successful year in operation. Mr. Johnson has earned a Bachelor of Science in Mathematics from Longwood College, a Masters in Education from North Georgia State University and Educational Specialist degree in Educational Leadership from Jones University.</p>
          </blockquote>
          <p><img align="right" title="2015 STEM Rebecca Johnson" alt="2015 STEM Rebecca Johnson" src="/uploadedImages/Conferences/STEM/Rebecca Johnson_web.jpg?n=9200">-Rebecca Johnson, Facilitator of Gifted Resources,&nbsp;Accomack County Public Schools</p>
